description: Seokchon Lake was originally the main channel of the Han River flowing through the center of Seoul. When the Han River was filled, part of the waterway was cut off and it became a lake. Then it flourished and became Shicun Lake Park. After Songpo Road was completed, Shicun Lake Park was divided into East Lake and West Lake. Nearby citizens like to go to East Lake, while those who come to West Lake are mainly tourists who go to "Magic Iceland". The park is beautifully repaired and the scenery is beautiful. In the morning, residents will be seen doing morning exercises, which can be close to the daily life of the Korean people. In early April, the Shichun Lake Cherry Blossom Festival will also be held here. There will also be a variety of performances during the festival, such as classical music, magic, face painting, etc., as well as various traditional folk games, which are very interesting.

The Seoul Museum of History is a city history museum that introduces the history and culture of Seoul. The museum opened to the public in May 2002. The museum is divided into several different exhibition halls, showing the style and appearance of ancient Seoul and the necessities of life of modern Seoul people. The museum preserves historical materials about the changes of Seoul from prehistoric times to the present, and a considerable part of the exhibits are ancient Seoul cultural relics donated by citizens. People can get to know and know about Seoul through different exhibits.

The North Seoul Dream Forest located in Gangbuk District, built in 1989, is the only natural oxygen bar in Gangbuk District, Seoul. Covering an area of 33 hectares, it is a family-friendly tourist attraction.

The indoor stadium is located at the Seoul Sports Complex in Jamsil-dong, Songpa-gu, Seoul. Since its completion in 1979, it has been used as a performance venue for indoor ball games and various events. The 1986 Seoul Asian Games and the 1988 Seoul Olympics basketball games were held here.

South Korea's Jurassic Dinosaur Museum restores the real dinosaur experience, the new Hammond Genetics Institute, observes all dinosaurs at close range, the exhibition incorporates interactive educational elements, the giant dinosaur parent-child garden, parent-child interaction, and popularize dinosaur knowledge together.

Located in Seoul, South Korea, the Central Mosque is a mosque built in Itaewon, Seoul and officially opened in 1976. The mosque offers worship in English, Arabic, Korean and other languages. Every Friday at 1:00 p.m., a large number of believers come, and most of them are Arabs, Indians, and Pakistani Korean migrant workers.

On the left of Seoul Square is Deoksugung Palace, on the right is the well-known Myeongdong neighborhood, and there is a Seoul Library next to the square. The square is equipped with fountains, 48 lights, and attractions such as the circular clock - the strike. In particular, the circular clock has become a landmark of Seoul Plaza. The square is so clean that visitors can walk barefoot or rest in the warm sunshine in the afternoon. In winter, the square will be transformed into an ice skating rink, bringing people a different kind of fun. The skating rink is divided into a general area and a children's area, and there are convenient facilities such as places for rest, shops, and cafes nearby. After night falls, the lights come on, making it even more romantic for people to experience the romantic feeling of skating in a dreamlike atmosphere. Whether it is a lover in love, or a middle school student who comes to play with classmates, you will have a good time here. In addition, Seoul Plaza often hosts various cultural events. Citizens or tourists can come here to participate in various cultural activities such as concerts, youth literary and art exhibitions, and sculpture exhibitions.
